  "datePublished": "2026-03-08",
  "description": "Quantization is the process of reducing the numerical precision of a neural network\u0026rsquo;s weights — from their original 16-bit floating point (FP16) to fewer bits (typically 2–8 bits). This reduces file size and memory usage, and increases inference speed because fewer bytes need to be loaded from memory per operation.\nThe trade-off is accuracy: fewer bits means less precise weight representation, which can degrade model output quality. The degradation is minimal at 8-bit (Q8_0) and becomes noticeable below 4-bit.\n",
  "name": "quantization",
